     =20
      <br>
        <br>
        <br>
        <span class=3D"TimesBlack16">The <span class=3D"TimesBlue16"><stron=
g>interior angles</strong></span> of a polygon are the angles at each verte=
x on the inside of the polygon. <br>
        In convex polygons, each interior angle is always less than 180=C2=
=BA<br>
      Do not confuse <span class=3D"TimesBlue16">"interior angles" </span>w=
ith <span class=3D"TimesDarkRed16">"central angles".</span><br>
      The vertex of an <span class=3D"TimesBlue16">"interior angle"</span> =
is a<span class=3D"TimesBlue16"> vertex of any polgon. </span><br>
      The vertex of a<span class=3D"TimesDarkRed16"> "central angle" </span=
>is the <span class=3D"TimesDarkRed16">center of a regular polygon,</span><=
br>
      <br>
      </span>
      <div><span class=3D"TimesBlack16">Some interior angles are well known=
 and/or easy to find.</span></div>
      <table width=3D"98%" border=3D"1" cellpadding=3D"5" cellspacing=3D"0"=
 class=3D"blackborderfine">
        <tbody><tr>
          <td width=3D"33%" valign=3D"top"><div align=3D"center"><img src=
=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Geometry/Polygons/angle1.jpg" width=3D"158=
" height=3D"130" alt=3D"angle1"><br>
            <span class=3D"TimesBlack14">We have proven that the sum of the=
 measures of the interior angles of a triangle is 180=C2=BA.<br>
              We can easily find that <em>x</em>=C2=BA =3D 45=C2=BA.</span>=
</div></td>
          <td width=3D"33%" valign=3D"top"><div align=3D"center"><img src=
=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Geometry/Polygons/angle2a.jpg" width=3D"18=
8" height=3D"130" alt=3D"angle2"><br>
            <span class=3D"TimesBlack14">A regular triangle is an </span><s=
pan class=3D"TimesBlue14"><strong>equilateral</strong></span> <span class=
=3D"TimesBlack14">triangle with all sides and angles of equal measure.     =
       We only need to divide 180 by 3 to find the size of each angle.</spa=
n></div></td>
          <td width=3D"34%" valign=3D"top"><div align=3D"center"><img src=
=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Geometry/Polygons/angle3.jpg" width=3D"150=
" height=3D"130" alt=3D"angle3"><br>
              <span class=3D"TimesBlack14">When dealing with 4-sided polygo=
ns, a diagonal divides the figure into two triangles showing that the sum o=
f the interior angles must be 2(180) =3D 360=C2=BA. </span></div></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody></table>
      <p class=3D"TimesBlack16">The strategy shown in the quadrilateral, of=
 dividing the figure into triangles, will be used to investigate the  inter=
ior angles of polygons with more than four sides.  <br>
        This strategy may be referred to as  <strong>"decomposing"</strong>=
, "<strong>partitioning</strong>" or "<strong>dissecting</strong>".</p>
      <div><span class=3D"TimesBlack16">If we use diagonals to partition a =
polygon into  a series of triangles (as was done with the quadrilateral),=
=20
        we can calculate the sum of the interior angles of larger-sided pol=
ygons. </span></div>
      <div align=3D"left" class=3D"TimesBlack16"></div>
      <table width=3D"94%" border=3D"1" cellpadding=3D"5" cellspacing=3D"0"=
 class=3D"blackborder">
        <tbody><tr>
          <td width=3D"50%" valign=3D"top"><div align=3D"left" class=3D"Tim=
esBlack16">In a <span class=3D"TimesBlue16"><strong>regular hexagon</strong=
></span>, four triangles can be created using diagonals of the hexagon from=
 a common vertex. Since the interior angles of each triangle total 180=C2=
=BA, the hexagon's interior angles will total 4(180=C2=BA), or 720=C2=BA.</=
div>
            <div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/=
Geometry/Polygons/polydiaganglesa.jpg" width=3D"174" height=3D"185" alt=3D"=
polydigangles">
            </div>
            <div align=3D"center" class=3D"TimesBlack16"></div></td>
          <td width=3D"50%" valign=3D"top"><div align=3D"left">
            <div class=3D"TimesBlack14"><span class=3D"TimesBlack16">This s=
ame approach can be taken in  an <span class=3D"TimesBlue16"><strong>irregu=
lar hexagon</strong></span>. The diagonals form four triangles whose interi=
or angles total 180=C2=BA, giving the hexagon's interior angles a total of =
4(180=C2=BA), or 720=C2=BA.</span></div>
            <div align=3D"center" class=3D"TimesBlack14"><img src=3D"https:=
//mathbitsnotebook.com/Geometry/Polygons/polydiagangles2.jpg" width=3D"195"=
 height=3D"185" alt=3D"irreghexagon"></div>
          </div></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td colspan=3D"2" valign=3D"top" class=3D"TimesBlack16"><div alig=
n=3D"center">
            <strong>Notice</strong> that the sum of the interior angles is =
the same<br>
              for both the <strong>regular</strong> and the <strong>irregul=
ar</strong> hexagons.

            <strong><br>
            <br>
            Also notice</strong> that we formed 4 triangles in the hexagon,=
 <br>
            which is 2 less than the number of sides of the polygon.<br>
            <br>
            The sum of the interior angles is <span class=3D"TimesBlue16"><=
strong>180=C2=BA =E2=80=A2 (the number of triangles formed)</strong></span>=
 or 180=E2=80=A2(<em>n</em> - 2).
              <br>
                    =20
          </div></td>
          </tr>
      </tbody></table>
      <p class=3D"TimesBlack16">The pattern developed in the example above,=
 is consistent for ALL polygons.</p>
