      <table width=3D"392" border=3D"1" align=3D"left" class=3D"blackborder=
green">
        <tbody><tr>
          <td class=3D"ArialBlack20"><div align=3D"center" class=3D"ArialBl=
ack24">Exterior Angles</div></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody></table>
      <br>
      <p>&nbsp;</p>
      <div><span class=3D"TimesBlack16">We  discussed the concept of an <a =
href=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Geometry/SegmentsAnglesTriangles/SATEx=
teriorAngle.html">exterior angle of a triangle</a> in a previous section.</=
span></div>
      <table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0">
        <tbody><tr>
          <td width=3D"77%" valign=3D"top" class=3D"TimesBlack16">The exter=
ior angle of a triangle is formed by one side of the triangle and the exten=
sion of an adjacent side of the triangle. We will now extend this concept t=
o polygons. </td>
          <td width=3D"23%"><img src=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Geomet=
ry/Polygons/angle4.jpg" width=3D"148" height=3D"64" alt=3D"angle4"></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody></table>
      <p class=3D"TimesBlack16">The <span class=3D"TimesBlue16"><strong>ext=
erior angle</strong></span> of a polygon is an angle that forms a linear pa=
ir=20
        with one of the interior angles of the polygon. In the same manner =
as an exterior angle of a triangle, the exterior angle of a polygon is  for=
med by any side of the polygon and the extension of its adjacent side.</p>
               </div>
                 <table width=3D"94%" border=3D"1" align=3D"center" cellpad=
ding=3D"5" cellspacing=3D"0" class=3D"blackborder">
                   <tbody><tr>
                     <td width=3D"51%" valign=3D"top"><div align=3D"left" c=
lass=3D"TimesBlack16">The  <span class=3D"TimesBlue16"><strong>exterior ang=
le of a polygon</strong></span>  is formed by any side of the polygon and t=
he extension of its adjacent side. <span class=3D"TimesBlue16"><strong>Exte=
rior angles and interior angles are supplementary</strong></span> and form =
a linear pair. If the polygon is regular, all of its exterior angles will b=
e the same measure. </div>
                       <div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://mathbitsno=
tebook.com/Geometry/Polygons/exangle3.jpg" width=3D"241" height=3D"240" alt=
=3D"extang3"></div>
<div align=3D"center" class=3D"TimesBlack16"></div></td>
                     <td width=3D"49%" valign=3D"top"><div align=3D"left">
                       <div class=3D"TimesBlack14"><span class=3D"TimesBlac=
k16">There are actually </span><span class=3D"TimesBlack16">two congruent e=
xterior angles at each vertex</span><span class=3D"TimesBlack16">, but </sp=
an><span class=3D"TimesBlue16"><strong>only ONE will be considered for our =
work.</strong></span><span class=3D"TimesBlack16"> Shown below, =E2=88=A01 =
and =E2=88=A02 are exterior angles and are also congruent vertical angles. =
Note that =E2=88=A03 is NOT an exterior angle, but it is congruent to inter=
ior=E2=88=A0<em>CDE</em> as they are vertical angles.</span></div>
                       <div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://mathbitsno=
tebook.com/Geometry/Polygons/exangle2a.jpg" width=3D"228" height=3D"185" al=
t=3D"exangle2a">
                       </div>
                       <div align=3D"center" class=3D"TimesBlack14"></div>
                     </div></td>
                   </tr>
                 </tbody></table>
                 <p align=3D"center"><span class=3D"TimesBlack16">         =
         If you add ALL exterior angles (ONE at a vertex), you will get a s=
um of 360=C2=BA.<br>
                   The sum of the exterior angles of <strong>ALL</strong> p=
olygons is a </span><span class=3D"TimesBlue16"><strong>constant 360=C2=BA.=
</strong></span><br>
                 </p>
