4">Regular </span></strong>Polygon</div></td>
                         <td width=3D"32%"><div class=3D"TimesBlack24"><img=
 src=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Geometry/Polygons/exang2.gif" alt=3D"e=
xang2" width=3D"93" height=3D"80"><br>
                         </div></td>
                       </tr>
                     </tbody></table></td>
                   </tr>
                 </tbody></table>
                 <p>&nbsp;</p>
                 <table width=3D"672" border=3D"1" align=3D"center" cellpad=
ding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" class=3D"blackborder">
                   <tbody><tr>
                     <td width=3D"655"><table width=3D"668" border=3D"0" ce=
llpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0">
                       <tbody><tr>
                         <td width=3D"130" valign=3D"bottom"><div align=3D"=
center"><img src=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Geometry/Polygons/confused=
Guy.jpg" width=3D"162" height=3D"128" alt=3D"confusedGuy"> </div></td>
                         <td width=3D"528"><div align=3D"left" class=3D"Tim=
esBlack16"><span class=3D"ArialBlack16">So <strong>WHY</strong> do the exte=
rior angles (taken one at a vertex) always add up to 360=C2=BA regardless o=
f the number of sides of the polygon?</span></div></td>
                       </tr>
                     </tbody></table></td>
                   </tr>
                 </tbody></table>
                 <p class=3D"TimesBlack16">Here is what we know about exter=
ior angles and polygons:<br>
                   <br>
                 <strong>1.</strong> A  polygon with <em>n</em> sides will =
have  <em>n</em> interior angles and <em>n</em> exterior angles (one at eac=
h vertex).<br>
                 <strong><br>
                 2.</strong> By its  formation, an exterior angle is supple=
mentary to its adjacent interior angle.<br>
                 <strong><br>
                 3.</strong> At each vertex of the polygon, the interior an=
gle and the exterior angle form a linear pair. Since there are <em>n</em> v=
ertices, there will be <em>n</em> linear pairs in total around the polygon.=
 Each linear pair adds to 180=C2=BA for a total of <em>n</em> =E2=80=A2 180=
=C2=BA or 180<em>n </em>degrees around the polygon.<br>
                 <strong><br>
                 4.</strong> We have already shown that the formula for the=
 sum of the interior angles of a polygon with <em>n</em> sides is 180(<em>n=
</em> - 2).<br>
                 <strong><br>
                 5.</strong> From the sum of ALL linear pairs (180<em>n</em=
>), subtract the sum of the interior angles (the formula). You will be left=
 with the sum of the exterior angles. </p>
                 <p align=3D"center" class=3D"TimesBlack16"><span class=3D"=
TimesBlack20">                 180<em>n</em> - 180(<em>n</em> - 2) =3D 180<=
em>n</em> - 180<em>n</em> + 360 =3D 0 + 360 =3D 360.</span><br>
                   The sum of the exterior angles is constant (360=C2=BA) f=
or ALL polygons!!!
                   <br>
                   <br>
                 </p>
                 <table width=3D"95%" border=3D"1" cellpadding=3D"5" cellsp=
acing=3D"0" class=3D"blackborderfine">
                   <tbody><tr>
                     <td><table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0">
                       <tbody><tr>
                         <td width=3D"24%" valign=3D"top"><img src=3D"https=
://mathbitsnotebook.com/Geometry/Images/ExamplePin1.jpg" width=3D"160" heig=
ht=3D"45" alt=3D"ex1"></td>
                         <td width=3D"76%" class=3D"ArialBlack16">Find the =
<span class=3D"ArialBlue16"><strong>sum</strong></span> of the <span class=
=3D"ArialBlue16"><strong>exterior</strong></span> angles of a hexagon. Of  =
a pentagon. Of a dodecagon. Of a quadrilateral. Of a 17-gon.</td>
                       </tr>
                       <tr>
                         <td valign=3D"top">&nbsp;</td>
                         <td class=3D"TimesRed16">All of these answers are =
the same. The sum of the exterior angles is 360=C2=BA.<br>
                           <br></td>
                       </tr>
                       <tr>
                         <td valign=3D"top"><img src=3D"https://mathbitsnot=
ebook.com/Geometry/Images/ExamplePin2.jpg" width=3D"160" height=3D"45" alt=
=3D"ex2"></td>
                         <td class=3D"ArialBlack16">How many <span class=3D=
"ArialBlue16"><b>sides </b></span>does a polygon have if the <span class=3D=
"ArialBlue16"><strong>sum</strong></span> of the <span class=3D"ArialBlue16=
"><strong>exterior</strong></span> angles is 360=C2=BA?</td>
                       </tr>
                       <tr>
                         <td valign=3D"top">&nbsp;</td>
                         <td class=3D"TimesRed16">This is a trick question.=
 The sum of the exterior angles of ALL polygons is 360=C2=BA. There is insu=
fficient information to determine the number of sides.<br>
                         <br></td>
                       </tr>
                       <tr>
                         <td valign=3D"top"><img src=3D"https://mathbitsnot=
ebook.com/Geometry/Images/ExamplePin3.jpg" width=3D"160" height=3D"45" alt=
=3D"ex3"></td>
                         <td class=3D"ArialBlack16">Find the measure of <sp=
an class=3D"ArialRed16"><strong>each exterior</strong></span> angle of a <s=
pan class=3D"ArialRed16"><strong>regular</strong></span> octagon.</td>
                       </tr>
                       <tr>
                         <td valign=3D"top">&nbsp;</td>
                         <td class=3D"ArialBlack16"><span class=3D"TimesRed=
16">This is  a regular polygon, so we can use the formula. An octagon has 8=
 sides. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 360/<em>n</em> =3D 360/8 =3D 45=C2=BA</span><br>
                           <br>
                         </td>
                       </tr>
                       <tr>
                         <td valign=3D"top"><img src=3D"https://mathbitsnot=
ebook.com/Geometry/Images/ExamplePin4.jpg" width=3D"160" height=3D"45" alt=
=3D"ex4"></td>
                         <td class=3D"ArialBlack16">Each <span class=3D"Ari=
alRed16"><strong>exterior </strong></span>angle of a <span class=3D"ArialRe=
d16"><strong>regular</strong></span> polygon contains 40=C2=BA. Find the nu=
mber of <span class=3D"ArialRed16"><strong>sides</strong></span> of the pol=
ygon.</td>
                       </tr>
                       <tr>
                         <td valign=3D"top">&nbsp;</td>
                         <td class=3D"TimesRed16">This is a regular polygon=
, so use the formula. Set the formula equal to 40 and solve for <em>n</em>.=
<br>                           <img src=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Geo=
metry/Polygons/exforml.png" alt=3D"exforml" width=3D"83" height=3D"100"><br=
></td>
                       </tr>
                     </tbody></table></td>
                   </tr>
                 </tbody></table>
                 <p align=3D"center" class=3D"ArialBlack16"><br>
                 <img src=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Geometry/Images/g=
eodivider.jpg" width=3D"495" height=3D"10" alt=3D"divider"></p>
